---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const realtorBody = `
  

  <!-- ============ SECTION 0: HERO ============ -->
  <header class="hero hero--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-text">
          <div class="hero-eyebrow eyebrow">Real Estate Agent Mortgages</div>
          <h1 class="display-1">Real estate agent mortgage from a lender who reads Schedule C 1099 commission, 2-year income averaging, team override revenue, brokerage stock comp, post-NAR-settlement commission structure, and Form 1084 addbacks as one income picture.</h1>
          <p class="lead hero-subtitle">Working U.S. real estate agents and brokers carry the most income-volatile self-employment profile of any sales profession &mdash; and one of the trickiest to qualify under standard underwriting. <strong>Per BLS OOH May 2024 data, real estate sales agents run a median wage of $54,300 and real estate brokers run $63,060. But these medians are misleading for serious producers: established top-producing agents commonly earn $150K&ndash;$500K through gross commission income (GCI) net of brokerage split, luxury real estate brokers handling $1M+ home sales commonly earn $300K&ndash;$1M+, commercial real estate brokers $200K&ndash;$1M+, and team leaders with buyer&rsquo;s agent teams underneath them commonly $400K&ndash;$2M+ through combined personal production plus team override income</strong>. Income runs almost entirely through 1099-NEC Schedule C self-employment with substantial seasonal volatility, year-over-year market-cycle swings, and significant business deductions for marketing, vehicle, home office, MLS subscriptions, brokerage fees, and team support staff. Post-NAR commission settlement (March 2024 announcement, August 2024 effective date), buyer-side commission structures have shifted, adding another layer of income documentation nuance. The qualifying mechanic that matters: properly applied <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--paper); text-decoration: underline;">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a> Schedule C self-employment analysis with 2-year averaging, Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks for non-cash deductions, and proper treatment of multi-source revenue (personal commission + team override + brokerage stock comp + rental management) gets working real estate professionals into homes their straight-line W-2 income picture would never support.</p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Talk to Our Team</a>
            <a href="#income-methods" class="btn btn-secondary btn-large">See how realtor qualifying works</a>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-trust">
            <span class="trust-dot"></span>
            <span>Broker NMLS #1072866</span>
            <span>&middot;</span>
            <span>Specialist in Schedule C 1099 commission, 2-year income averaging, team override revenue, brokerage stock comp, NAR commission settlement, &amp; Form 1084 addbacks for real estate agent mortgages</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="hero-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/8293778/pexels-photo-8293778.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1200" alt="Real estate agent showing home to buyers" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1200x1500/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Realtors';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ============ STATS BAR ============ -->
  <section class="stats stats--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-bar-grid">
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$150K-$500K+</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Established top-producing real estate agent gross commission income net of brokerage split (BLS median of $54,300 misrepresents serious producer earnings)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">B3-3.3-02</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Fannie Mae rule for Schedule C self-employed income with 2-year averaging plus Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks &mdash; the central qualifying mechanic for working realtors</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">2-year average</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Standard qualifying period for self-employed Schedule C income (single-year income spikes don&rsquo;t support qualifying alone; 2 years of consistent earning required)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$1.6M+</div>
            <div class="stat-label">U.S. licensed real estate agents per NAR membership and ARELLO state license tracking (highly fragmented profession with brokerage diversity)</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="stats-bar-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/8292864/pexels-photo-8292864.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1000" alt="Real estate agent at open house" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1000x750/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Real+Estate';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ LEDE ============ -->
  <section class="lede-section">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="lede">Stairway Mortgage qualifies working real estate agents and brokers on the full income picture &mdash; <strong>Schedule C 1099-NEC commission income from buyer-side and listing-side transactions under Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02 with 2-year averaging applied to gross commission income (GCI) net of brokerage split and team support obligations, team override revenue for team leaders earning a percentage of buyer&rsquo;s agent and listing agent production within their team structure typically running 25-50 percent of team agent GCI, brokerage stock compensation including eXp World Holdings (eXp Realty) equity awards and revenue share program income, post-NAR-commission-settlement buyer-broker compensation structures including buyer-broker fee agreements treated as 1099 commission income, real estate investment income from agent-owned rental properties under B3-3.5-01 cash-flow analysis, brokerage W-2 base salary where applicable for hybrid brokerage models offering small base plus commission split, property management income for agents who manage their own and clients&rsquo; rental portfolios, real estate education and coaching 1099 income for top producers offering training programs, S-corp election structures for established top producers paying themselves W-2 reasonable compensation plus K-1 distributions under B3-3.4-02, and Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks recovering non-cash Schedule C deductions for vehicle depreciation, home office, marketing and MLS subscriptions, agent equipment, and brokerage fees that suppress taxable income</strong>. A new-licensed agent in years 1-2 building book of business, an established producer at $150K-$250K GCI, a top-producing team leader at $400K-$1M+ with team override, a luxury brokerage agent handling $1M+ home sales, and a commercial real estate broker with mixed deal flow each get qualified using methods that fit their actual structure. <strong>Importantly: real estate agents are NOT eligible for Physician/Doctor Loan products at most specialty lenders &mdash; the path is properly-structured Conventional Conforming or Jumbo with rigorous B3-3.3-02 Schedule C analysis, supplemented by Bank Statement Program Non-QM and Asset-Depletion Non-QM as alternatives for irregular-income or post-record-year scenarios.</strong> We pick the right door before we quote. Or skip ahead: browse <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">every loan program</a>, run numbers on <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">100+ mortgage calculators</a>, or check <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/current-rates/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">today&apos;s rates</a>. For the parent hub and other sales professional paths, see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/sales-professionals/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">sales professionals mortgage hub</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #1: KEY FACTS ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 &middot; Real estate agent mortgage at a glance</div>
        <h2>Key facts every real estate agent should know before applying for a mortgage.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="key-facts-grid">
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">B3-3.3-02</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a>, Schedule C self-employment income qualifies with 2-year averaging plus Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks for non-cash deductions. Critical for realtors because Schedule C deductions for vehicle, home office, marketing, MLS subscriptions, and depreciation suppress taxable income that Form 1084 systematically restores.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">2-year average</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Single-year income spikes (record listing year, one big commercial deal, lottery transaction) don&rsquo;t support qualifying alone. The B3-3.3-02 2-year average is the operative qualifying number. Real estate market cyclicality (2022-2023 transaction volume drop) makes the averaging window critical &mdash; we time mortgage closings strategically relative to recent earning patterns.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">NAR settlement</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">The <a href="https://www.nar.realtor/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">National Association of REALTORS&reg;</a> commission settlement announced March 2024 (effective August 17, 2024) changed buyer-side commission structures. Buyer-broker fee agreements are now required, MLS no longer displays buyer compensation offers, and commissions are increasingly directly negotiated. Income documentation must reflect post-settlement transaction patterns.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">No Physician Loan</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Real estate agents are NOT eligible for Physician/Doctor Loan products at most specialty lenders. The optimal path is properly-structured Conventional Conforming or Jumbo with rigorous B3-3.3-02 Schedule C analysis, plus Bank Statement Program Non-QM and Asset-Depletion Non-QM as alternatives for specific scenarios.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #2: ROLE-STAGE SOLUTIONS ============ -->
  <section class="professions-section section-tinted">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Where you are in your real estate career</div>
        <h2>Real estate agent mortgage solutions for every career stage.</h2>
        <p>Each stage of a real estate sales career has its own qualifying logic. A new-licensed agent in their first 2 years building a book of business has a different mortgage path than an established producer at $200K GCI, a top-producing team leader with buyer&rsquo;s agents earning override income, a luxury brokerage agent at $1M+ price points, or a commercial real estate broker with longer deal cycles.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="professions-grid">

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">01</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">New-licensed agent (Years 1&ndash;2)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Recently licensed real estate agent building first book of business. Strong commission potential but limited 1099 history for B3-3.3-02 2-year averaging. Often combining with spouse W-2 or other income."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $40K&ndash;$90K Schedule C 1099 first 2 years</li>
            <li>2-year history not yet established for sole qualifying</li>
            <li>Co-borrower (spouse W-2) typically critical for qualifying</li>
            <li>Conventional with Schedule C + co-borrower documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See new-agent mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">02</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established producer (Years 3&ndash;7)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established residential agent with consistent 2-year+ production history. $150K-$250K GCI net of brokerage split. Possibly building toward team structure or considering S-corp election."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $150K&ndash;$250K Schedule C 1099 commission</li>
            <li>2-year history supports full B3-3.3-02 qualifying</li>
            <li>Form 1084 addbacks for marketing, vehicle, MLS, home office</li>
            <li>Conventional Conforming or Jumbo</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See established producer mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">03</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Top-producing team leader</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Top-producing agent with established team of buyer&rsquo;s agents and listing agents underneath. Personal production plus team override revenue. Often S-corp structured. $400K-$1M+ combined."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Personal commission $250K&ndash;$500K plus team override $150K&ndash;$500K+</li>
            <li>S-corp election typical: W-2 reasonable comp + K-1 distributions</li>
            <li>Multi-source documentation under B3-3.4-02 + B3-3.3-02</li>
            <li>Conventional Jumbo with full Form 1084 addbacks</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See team leader mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">04</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Luxury brokerage agent</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Agent at luxury brokerage (Compass, Douglas Elliman, The Agency, Sotheby&rsquo;s International, Christie&rsquo;s International, Berkshire Hathaway HomeServices) handling $1M+ home sales. Higher per-transaction GCI, fewer transactions."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $300K&ndash;$1M+ from lower transaction volume</li>
            <li>$1M+ home sales generate $25K&ndash;$60K+ GCI per side</li>
            <li>Income volatility &mdash; one luxury deal swings annual numbers</li>
            <li>Conventional Jumbo with careful 2-year averaging</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See luxury brokerage mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">05</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Commercial real estate broker</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Commercial real estate broker (CBRE, JLL, Cushman &amp; Wakefield, Marcus &amp; Millichap, Newmark, Colliers, or boutique commercial firms) handling office, retail, multifamily, industrial, or specialty commercial transactions."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $200K&ndash;$1M+ with longer deal cycles</li>
            <li>Deal cycles 6-24 months from listing through close</li>
            <li>Multi-year averaging often more representative than 2-year</li>
            <li>Bank Statement Non-QM or Asset-Depletion alternative paths</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See commercial broker mechanics</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #3: INCOME CALCULATION METHODS ============ -->
  <section class="section" id="income-methods">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">03 &middot; The qualification mechanics</div>
        <h2>How we calculate qualifying income for your real estate agent mortgage.</h2>
        <p>Four methods cover almost every real estate agent file we&rsquo;ve closed. The right method depends on your career stage, your brokerage structure, whether you operate as a team leader with override income, and whether your transaction pattern fits Schedule C 2-year averaging or alternative bank-statement / asset-depletion documentation.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Method 1 &mdash; Schedule C 1099 commission + B3-6-05 IDR-aware DTI (the realtor default)</h3>
      <p>The dominant pattern for working real estate agents. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a>, Schedule C self-employment income qualifies with 2-year averaging applied to net business income after Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks. Form 1084 systematically recovers non-cash deductions including vehicle depreciation (often $5K-$15K annually for agents with luxury vehicles), home office expense, depreciation on agent equipment, business meals exclusion adjustments, and amortization. The 2-year average becomes the qualifying monthly income. For agents in years 3+ with consistent 2-year history at $150K-$300K GCI, this method works smoothly. For agents with one record year and one weaker year, the average smooths to the middle &mdash; sometimes favorable, sometimes not. Strategic timing matters.</p>

      <h3>Method 2 &mdash; Multi-source agent (commission + team override + rental management)</h3>
      <p>For team leaders and top producers with diversified income streams beyond personal Schedule C commission. Team override income (commonly 25-50% of buyer&rsquo;s agent and listing agent GCI within the team structure) qualifies as additional Schedule C revenue under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a> with 2-year history. Property management revenue for agents managing rental portfolios (own properties plus clients&rsquo;) flows through Schedule C similarly. Real estate education and coaching 1099 income for top producers offering training programs aggregates under the same Schedule C analysis. Multi-source agents commonly aggregate $400K-$1M+ across personal commission, team override, property management, and education/coaching.</p>

      <h3>Method 3 &mdash; S-corp election (top producer optimization)</h3>
      <p>For established top producers who have made S-corp election typically at $200K-$300K+ of annual net Schedule C income to optimize self-employment tax. Under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/1361" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 1361</a> and <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, qualifying income combines S-corp W-2 reasonable compensation paid to the agent (typically $80K-$150K for real estate agent owner-operators) plus K-1 distributions from <a href="https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1120-s" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Form 1120-S</a> with 2-year history. Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks at the S-corp level recover any non-cash deductions. Real estate agent S-corp ownership is generally NOT classified as SSTB under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a> (real estate sales is not health/law/accounting/etc.), potentially qualifying for the full 20% QBI deduction.</p>

      <h3>Method 4 &mdash; Bank Statement Program Non-QM (alternative path)</h3>
      <p>For agents whose tax-return income picture doesn&rsquo;t reflect actual earning capacity due to aggressive Schedule C deduction strategies or single-record-year scenarios that don&rsquo;t fit B3-3.3-02 2-year averaging well. Bank Statement Program Non-QM products qualify on 12 or 24 months of business bank statement deposits as proxy for income, accepting alternative documentation outside the conventional Fannie Mae framework. Pricing is higher than Conventional (typically 0.75-1.5% rate premium) but the qualifying methodology accommodates real estate income patterns that conventional underwriting can&rsquo;t handle cleanly. Asset-Depletion Non-QM offers another alternative for agents with significant liquid reserves but irregular current income, amortizing liquid assets over 360 months as implied income.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #4: DARK SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/8292864/pexels-photo-8292864.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 760px;">
        <div class="eyebrow eyebrow-light">04 &middot; What generalist underwriting misses</div>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper);">The income most lenders refuse to count on a real estate agent file.</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.78);">Six income facts that show up consistently on working real estate agent files and that generalist lenders typically either ignore, mis-categorize, or refuse to apply correctly. Each one is documentable; the lender just has to read the realtor multi-source self-employment pattern properly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dark-grid">
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">A</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks recover Schedule C deductions</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Working real estate agents take substantial Schedule C deductions: vehicle depreciation under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/167" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">IRC Section 167</a> (often $5K-$15K annually for luxury vehicles used in showings), home office, MLS and brokerage subscriptions, agent equipment depreciation, business meals adjustments, and marketing expenses. These suppress taxable Schedule C net income that Form 1084 systematically restores under B3-3.3-02 cash-flow analysis. Generalist lenders may use Line 31 of Schedule C as qualifying income directly &mdash; missing $25K-$60K of addbacks that working realtors routinely have available.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">B</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Team override income for team leaders (25-50% of team GCI)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Top-producing real estate team leaders earn override income from buyer&rsquo;s agents and listing agents within their team structure, typically 25-50% of team agent GCI. For a team leader with 4-6 team agents producing $1M+ in team GCI annually, override income commonly adds $250K-$500K on top of personal commission. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a>, override revenue qualifies as additional Schedule C income with 2-year history. Generalist lenders often miss this stream entirely or classify it as "passive income not continuing."</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">C</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">eXp Realty stock compensation and revenue share</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">eXp Realty (eXp World Holdings, NASDAQ: EXPI) offers agents stock awards through the EXP Sustainable Equity Plan and Revenue Share program creating equity compensation for production milestones and downline agent sponsorship. eXp Realty agents commonly accumulate $25K-$200K+ of EXPI equity over multi-year tenure plus monthly Revenue Share distribution income. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-01</a> for equity vesting plus <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.3-02</a> for Revenue Share, these aggregate into the qualifying picture.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">D</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Real estate investment income (agent-owned rental portfolios)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Working real estate agents commonly invest in rental property alongside their sales practice &mdash; the dual-role pattern is one of the most common in the profession. Per <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-08/rental-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-08</a>, rental income from agent-owned properties under Schedule E qualifies with 2-year history, with Form 1084 addbacks for non-cash depreciation, mortgage interest, and operating expense adjustments. Established agents commonly own 3-15+ rental units generating $25K-$200K+ of supplementary annual income.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">E</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Post-NAR-settlement buyer-broker fee structures</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">The <a href="https://www.nar.realtor/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">NAR</a> commission settlement (March 2024 announcement, August 17, 2024 effective date) eliminated MLS-displayed buyer-broker compensation offers and required buyer-broker fee agreements. Post-settlement, buyer-side commissions are increasingly directly negotiated with buyer-broker fee agreements. The income documentation pattern has shifted: buyer-broker fee 1099-NEC from buyer direct payment, listing-side 1099 from listing brokerage unchanged. We document the post-settlement transaction structure properly.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">F</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Real estate education, coaching, and brokerage equity income</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Top-producing agents commonly diversify into real estate education and coaching (Tom Ferry, Mike Ferry, Brian Buffini, Keller Williams MAPS Coaching, eXp Bold) creating 1099 instructor income, course revenue, and speaking fees. Brokerage equity ownership for agents at smaller boutique brokerages, broker-owners at independent brokerages, and partial-equity team leaders at PE-backed brokerage rollups (Real Brokerage, Side, Place) creates additional income streams. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.3-02</a> and <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.4-02</a>, these aggregate.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #5: LOAN PROGRAM MATRIX ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">05 &middot; Match the program to your realtor situation</div>
        <h2>Which loan program fits your real estate agent mortgage situation.</h2>
