  <!-- ============ H2 #6: INDUSTRY CONTEXT ============ -->
  <section class="section section-tinted">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">06 &middot; Why this mortgage requires specialty expertise</div>
        <h2>The real estate agent mortgage in context: 6 forces shaping how realtors qualify.</h2>
        <p>Real estate agent mortgage qualifying sits at the intersection of the NAR commission settlement and post-August-2024 buyer-broker fee structure changes, brokerage industry consolidation and eXp Realty cloud brokerage growth, real estate transaction volume cyclicality, the team structure trend with override income dynamics, the dual-role investor-agent pattern, and real estate education and coaching industry growth. Each force shapes what a working agent&rsquo;s qualifying picture looks like.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Force 1 &mdash; NAR commission settlement and post-August-2024 buyer-broker fee structures</h3>
      <p>The <a href="https://www.nar.realtor/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">National Association of REALTORS&reg;</a> $418M class-action settlement announced March 2024 (effective August 17, 2024) fundamentally restructured real estate commission practices. MLS systems no longer display buyer-broker compensation offers; buyer-broker fee agreements between buyers and their agents are now required before showings; and buyer-side commissions are increasingly directly negotiated rather than seller-paid through the listing brokerage. The mortgage implication: post-settlement realtor income documentation increasingly shows buyer-broker fee 1099-NECs from buyer-direct payment alongside traditional listing-side 1099s from listing brokerages. We document the post-settlement transaction structure and the resulting income flow correctly.</p>

      <h3>Force 2 &mdash; Brokerage industry consolidation and eXp Realty cloud-brokerage growth</h3>
      <p>The U.S. residential brokerage landscape has consolidated substantially over the past decade through both traditional brokerage M&amp;A (Anywhere Real Estate / Realogy combining Coldwell Banker, Century 21, ERA, Sotheby&rsquo;s, Better Homes &amp; Gardens; Compass acquiring boutique brokerages; HomeServices of America/Berkshire Hathaway expansion) and cloud-brokerage disruption (eXp Realty/eXp World Holdings, Real Brokerage, LPT Realty, Place, Side). eXp Realty in particular has grown to over 90,000 agents through its cloud model offering agent equity compensation through EXPI stock awards and the Revenue Share program. The mortgage implication: brokerage stock comp (eXp Realty, Real Brokerage equity) is an increasingly important income component for cloud-brokerage agents.</p>

      <h3>Force 3 &mdash; Real estate transaction volume cyclicality</h3>
      <p>U.S. residential real estate transaction volume is highly cyclical with substantial year-over-year swings driven by interest rate cycles, housing supply dynamics, and consumer confidence. The 2022-2023 transaction volume drop following the 2021-2022 boom created a year-over-year income decline of 30-50% for many agents. Agents with strong 2021-2022 records but weak 2023 numbers face B3-3.3-02 2-year averaging that smooths to mid-range. The mortgage implication: timing of mortgage close relative to recent earning patterns matters strategically &mdash; we evaluate whether current 2-year average favors close now or post-rebound.</p>

      <h3>Force 4 &mdash; Team structure growth (top producers building teams)</h3>
      <p>The real estate team structure has become the dominant top-producer business model over the past 15 years. Real Trends and other industry data show top-producing agent teams (5+ agents under team leader) account for an increasing share of total residential transactions. Team leaders earn personal commission plus team override (commonly 25-50% of team agent GCI). The mortgage implication: team leaders carry substantially higher qualifying income through the override stream that generalist lenders often miss or mis-categorize.</p>

      <h3>Force 5 &mdash; Dual-role investor-agent pattern</h3>
      <p>The dual-role pattern of working real estate agent + rental property investor is one of the most common in the profession. Working agents have access, expertise, and deal flow that supports investment portfolio growth &mdash; making the investor-agent overlap natural. Established agents commonly own 3-15+ rental units. Per <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-08/rental-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-08</a>, rental income from agent-owned properties qualifies with Form 1084 addbacks recovering depreciation and operating expense items. The mortgage implication: dual-role agents carry rental income streams that substantially augment personal commission income for qualifying purposes.</p>

      <h3>Force 6 &mdash; Real estate education, coaching, and brokerage equity industry growth</h3>
      <p>The real estate education and coaching industry has grown substantially with top-producing agents diversifying into instructor and coaching roles. Major coaching organizations (Tom Ferry, Mike Ferry, Brian Buffini, Keller Williams MAPS Coaching, eXp Bold, Workman Success Systems) employ thousands of agent-coaches who earn 1099 instructor revenue, course revenue, and speaking fees in addition to personal sales production. Brokerage equity ownership has expanded as boutique broker-owners, PE-backed brokerage rollups (Real Brokerage, Side, Place), and partial-equity team leader structures create additional income streams. The mortgage implication: top producers commonly aggregate $400K-$2M+ across personal commission + team override + coaching/education + brokerage equity, requiring multi-source documentation.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

