            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/conventional-loan/">Conventional conforming details</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/jumbo-loan/">Jumbo loan details</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/purchase-inquiry/">Start your realtor mortgage pre-approval</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My net Schedule C income is much lower than my actual earning capacity. Can I still qualify?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; this is the central qualifying mechanic for working realtors. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a>, Form 1084 cash-flow analysis systematically adds back non-cash Schedule C deductions: vehicle depreciation, home office depreciation, equipment depreciation, business meal exclusion adjustments, amortization, and other non-cash items. The Form 1084 adjusted net income often runs $25K-$60K above Schedule C Line 31 for working realtors. We do the full addback analysis &mdash; not just Line 31.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a new-licensed agent in year 2. Can I qualify on my own without a co-borrower?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Limited. Under B3-3.3-02, 2-year self-employment history is the standard for sole-borrower qualifying. Year-1 agents typically cannot qualify alone on Schedule C income. Year-2 agents may qualify in some cases with strong year-2 numbers but underwriters apply conservative treatment. The realistic path for years 1-2: co-borrower (typically spouse W-2) plus partial Schedule C, then refinance into agent-only qualifying after 2-year history establishes.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">03</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the NAR commission settlement affect my mortgage qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">The August 17, 2024 effective date of the <a href="https://www.nar.realtor/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NAR settlement</a> changed buyer-side commission structures: MLS no longer displays buyer-broker compensation offers, buyer-broker fee agreements are required, and buyer-side commissions are increasingly directly negotiated. Post-settlement, your 1099-NEC structure may include buyer-direct payment 1099s alongside traditional listing-side brokerage 1099s. We document the post-settlement transaction patterns properly to maintain continuing-employment treatment under B3-3.3-02.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">04</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My team override income is 30% of my team&rsquo;s GCI. Does that count for qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; team override revenue (typically 25-50% of team agent GCI) qualifies as continuing Schedule C income under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a> with 2-year history. We document the team structure through the brokerage&rsquo;s team revenue-sharing agreement and 2 years of 1099-NEC override receipts. For top-producing team leaders, override commonly adds $150K-$500K+ on top of personal commission.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">05</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m an eXp Realty agent. How does the EXPI stock comp count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">eXp Realty stock awards through the EXP Sustainable Equity Plan qualify under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a> as continuing variable income with 2-year vesting history. The eXp Revenue Share program (monthly distributions from your downline agent sponsorship) qualifies as continuing Schedule C self-employment income under B3-3.3-02 with 2-year history. Combined eXp stock + Revenue Share commonly adds $20K-$60K+ for established eXp agents.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">06</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I own 6 rental properties as investments. Does that income help my qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; agent-owned rental income qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-08/rental-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-08</a> with 2-year Schedule E history. Form 1084 cash-flow analysis recovers non-cash deductions for depreciation and operating expense adjustments. 6 rental properties commonly generate $50K-$200K+ of supplementary qualifying income. The dual-role agent + investor pattern is one of the strongest mortgage qualifying profiles in the real estate profession.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">07</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My 2024 income was much lower than 2023. Will the 2-year average hurt me?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Possibly &mdash; the B3-3.3-02 2-year average smooths year-over-year volatility, which helps when current year is up but constrains when current year is down. For agents with strong 2021-2022 records but weaker 2023-2024 (the post-boom transaction volume decline scenario), strategic timing of mortgage close matters. Alternative paths: Bank Statement Program Non-QM uses 12 or 24 months of current bank deposits (may show stronger recent recovery), or Asset-Depletion Non-QM if liquid reserves are substantial.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I make S-corp election for my real estate practice?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically at $200K-$300K+ of annual net Schedule C income, S-corp election starts producing meaningful self-employment tax savings. S-corp election involves paying yourself W-2 reasonable compensation (typically $80K-$150K for real estate agents) and taking remaining profit as K-1 distributions. Coordinate timing with your CPA &mdash; the election typically must be made by March 15 for the current tax year. We can model the qualifying impact pre vs post S-corp election.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My broker said I qualify for a "real estate agent loan program." Are those real?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Limited. Some specialty lenders extend real-estate-specific products with relaxed self-employment documentation requirements similar in concept to Physician Loan but typically with smaller market presence than physician loans. The realistic answer: for most working realtors, properly-structured Conventional Conforming or Jumbo with rigorous B3-3.3-02 Schedule C analysis (plus Bank Statement Non-QM and Asset-Depletion alternatives) produces strong outcomes &mdash; what matters is the broker&rsquo;s self-employment underwriting expertise, not chasing specialty products that may not actually deliver better terms.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What documentation do I need for a real estate agent mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically: two complete federal 1040s with all schedules including Schedule C (sales practice) and Schedule E (rental properties); if S-corp, Form 1120-S returns with K-1s and Schedule L; all 1099-NECs from brokerages and any buyer-direct payments; 60 days of personal and business bank statements; current state real estate license; brokerage affiliation documentation; any team revenue-sharing agreements if team leader; eXp Realty equity statements if applicable.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates higher for real estate agents?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Conventional Conforming and Jumbo rates are the same for real estate agents as for any other borrower at the same credit profile when qualifying through standard B3-3.3-02 Schedule C analysis. Bank Statement Program Non-QM products carry a 0.75-1.5% rate premium vs Conventional but offer alternative documentation flexibility. Asset-Depletion Non-QM similar premium. We compare programs case-by-case considering documentation needs and expected hold period.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My commercial brokerage has 12-24 month deal cycles. Does that affect 2-year averaging?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; commercial real estate broker income volatility (driven by 6-24 month deal cycles) creates 2-year averages that may not reflect underlying earning capacity. For commercial brokers with multi-year track records, we sometimes argue for 3-year or longer averaging window to capture deal cycle smoothing, though standard B3-3.3-02 caps at 2-year average. Alternative: Bank Statement Program Non-QM with 24-month documentation often handles commercial broker income patterns more flexibly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My spouse is also a real estate agent. How does that affect us?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Two-agent households produce strong joint qualifying when both spouses have established 2-year Schedule C histories. Both files combine as co-borrowers with full B3-3.3-02 analysis on each Schedule C. Combined GCI of $300K-$600K plus joint Form 1084 addbacks commonly supports $1M-$1.8M qualifying. Watch-out: if both spouses had weak 2023-2024 transaction years, the joint 2-year average reflects the combined dip &mdash; strategic timing matters.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I do real estate coaching for Tom Ferry. How does coaching 1099 income count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Real estate coaching, education, and instructor 1099 income from <a href="https://www.tomferry.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Tom Ferry</a>, Mike Ferry, Brian Buffini, Keller Williams MAPS Coaching, eXp Bold, or other organizations qualifies as continuing Schedule C self-employment under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a> with 2-year history. We document the coaching agreement structure and 2-year billing history. Coaching income commonly adds $30K-$150K+ for top-producer coaches.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My brokerage is on Compass with stock comp. How does Compass equity work for qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Compass (NYSE: COMP) historically offered stock awards to agents during pre-IPO and early-IPO periods. Compass agent equity is much less prevalent in current grant structures. Existing Compass agent equity holdings qualify under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a> as continuing variable income with vesting history. eXp Realty (eXp World Holdings, NASDAQ: EXPI) is the more common cloud-brokerage with active agent equity programs currently.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I qualify on bank statements alone instead of tax returns?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes through Bank Statement Program Non-QM products. These programs qualify on 12 or 24 months of business bank statement deposits as proxy for income, treating deposits as gross revenue and applying an expense factor (typically 50-60%) to derive net qualifying income. Useful for agents whose tax returns show heavy deductions suppressing taxable income or for agents in growth phases where current bank deposits exceed prior-year tax return income. Rate premium of 0.75-1.5% vs Conventional. We compare against Conventional B3-3.3-02 pricing to determine which path is optimal.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I have significant reserves from a record 2021 commission year. Can I use Asset-Depletion?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; Asset-Depletion Non-QM qualifies on liquid asset reserves amortized over 360 months as implied income. Useful for top producers post-record-year with significant liquid reserves but irregular current-year income that doesn&rsquo;t fit B3-3.3-02 2-year averaging well. $500K of qualifying liquid assets amortizes to roughly $1,400/month of implied income; $2M to $5,500/month. We model Asset-Depletion alongside Conventional and Bank Statement to identify the optimal path.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a luxury brokerage agent with only 8-12 transactions per year. Does that volatility hurt qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes and no. Lower-frequency higher-per-transaction luxury brokerage income creates year-over-year volatility but the 2-year average under B3-3.3-02 smooths most of it. For luxury brokerage agents with strong 2-year combined histories, the average qualifies normally. For luxury agents whose 2-year window includes one very strong and one very weak year, strategic timing matters &mdash; we evaluate whether current 2-year average favors close now or post-rebound.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the IRS Section 199A QBI deduction affect me as a real estate agent?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Real estate sales practice is generally NOT classified as Specified Service Trade or Business (SSTB) under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a> &mdash; real estate sales is not in the SSTB list (which covers health, law, accounting, consulting, and similar services). Real estate agents typically qualify for the full 20% QBI deduction without SSTB phase-out limitations, regardless of income level. This is favorable vs medical practice owners and other SSTB-classified professionals.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m considering acquiring a small brokerage. How does that fit with personal mortgage qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Brokerage acquisition financing typically runs through <a href="https://www.sba.gov/funding-programs/loans/7a-loans" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SBA 7(a)</a> up to $5M or conventional business acquisition financing. We sequence the personal mortgage either BEFORE the brokerage acquisition closes (qualifying on established Schedule C agent history) or AFTER the acquired brokerage integrates with established post-acquisition revenue history. The brokerage acquisition adds business debt that affects personal DTI but also adds business income that supports qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My team broker-in-charge says my team revenue is "split with the brokerage." How do we document my actual income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Team revenue typically flows: agent GCI received by brokerage, brokerage retains its split, remainder to team account, team account distributes to team leader and team agents per the team agreement. Your 1099-NEC reflects what hit your personal income from this flow. We document the brokerage&rsquo;s team revenue-sharing agreement, your team&rsquo;s internal revenue-sharing structure, and your personal 1099-NEC receipt history. The personal 1099-NEC numbers are what qualifies under B3-3.3-02.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use unsold listing inventory or pending sales as qualifying income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No &mdash; only realized commission income from closed transactions qualifies under B3-3.3-02. Pending sales, active listings, signed contracts that haven&rsquo;t closed, and projected income don&rsquo;t count. The 2-year average uses historical Schedule C realized commission income only.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 120-150 days before you intend to make an offer. Real estate agent files benefit from significant runway because of full Schedule C Form 1084 cash-flow analysis, possible multi-source documentation (commission + override + rental + coaching + brokerage equity), S-corp 1120-S review if applicable, and strategic timing assessment relative to recent 2-year averaging window. For agents considering S-corp election, the conversation should happen 12+ months before mortgage close to allow election timing to season.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My broker said realtors should always use Bank Statement Programs because tax returns kill them. Is that right?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Partially correct, partially misleading. Bank Statement Non-QM helps when Schedule C deductions aggressively suppress tax return income that Form 1084 addbacks can&rsquo;t fully restore. But Conventional B3-3.3-02 with proper Form 1084 cash-flow analysis often produces equivalent or better qualifying at lower rates &mdash; the issue is finding a broker who does the full Form 1084 work properly. We model both paths against each other case-by-case before choosing.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do generalist lenders refuse real estate agent files when income is clearly there?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Four reasons: (1) generalist lenders use Schedule C Line 31 directly instead of running Form 1084 cash-flow analysis, missing $25K-$60K of addbacks; (2) team override income gets refused as "variable not stable" rather than properly aggregated under B3-3.3-02 with 2-year history; (3) eXp Realty equity and Revenue Share gets refused as "passive not continuing" rather than recognized as continuing self-employment income; (4) multi-source files (commission + override + rental + coaching) overwhelm generalist underwriters who don&rsquo;t routinely handle 4-5 simultaneous income streams. The income is all there and verifiable &mdash; the file just needs a broker who reads working realtor multi-source structure correctly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

